so that she can remain the queen of Ithaca.

266
00:18:56.810 --> 00:18:59.670
I'm tired of being
queen of Ithaca without her king!

267
00:18:59.979 --> 00:19:00.990
Without your king?

268
00:19:02.789 --> 00:19:03.789
Or without a king?

269
00:19:05.409 --> 00:19:07.790
And you think you're ready
take your father's place?

270
00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:10.890
That kid.

271
00:19:21.894 --> 00:19:23.390
Too loud. Melanthios.

272
00:19:23.784 --> 00:19:27.690
Do not wear spurs in the palace.
you are a cowherd. not a rider.

273
00:19:27.691 --> 00:19:30.870
And you're a pig farmer. who are you?
you talking to me like that?

274
00:19:31.429 --> 00:19:34.770
The servant whom our master left
in charge of his shepherds.

275
00:19:35.370 --> 00:19:38.470
The Lord is long gone
you old blind fool.

276
00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:42.170
And you're probably here
welcome. like the dog.

277
00:19:42.810 --> 00:19:43.810
Argos!

278
00:19:47.370 --> 00:19:48.370
Argos!

279
00:19:49.910 --> 00:19:50.910
Argos!

280
00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:52.290
Argos!

281
00:19:54.959 --> 00:19:55.959
He didn't do anything.

282
00:19:56.030 --> 00:19:57.030
So the stench is coming off you?

283
00:19:58.230 --> 00:19:59.550
Leave that old dog alone.

284
00:20:00.150 --> 00:20:00.690
Which one?

285
00:20:00.870 --> 00:20:01.870
Both of us.

286
00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:04.130
What did you tell him. Slade?

287
00:20:04.150 --> 00:20:05.150
He just got carried away.

288
00:20:05.190 --> 00:20:06.950
Argos is my father's hunting dog.

289
00:20:07.100 --> 00:20:08.100
His hunting dog?

290
00:20:12.210 --> 00:20:13.210
Look at that thing.

291
00:20:14.929 --> 00:20:16.186
Get him out of here before I eat him.

292
00:20:16.210 --> 00:20:16.570
No!

293
00:20:16.650 --> 00:20:17.730
Can't you see he's suffering?

294
00:20:18.450 --> 00:20:19.450
Good.

295
00:20:19.859 --> 00:20:21.259
So I'll put him out of his misery.

296
00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:22.390
Leave him alone!

297
00:20:40.030 --> 00:20:41.030
Do you see?

298
00:20:42.135 --> 00:20:43.135
Can you all see this?

299
00:20:44.990 --> 00:20:46.070
He attacked me!

300
00:20:47.050 --> 00:20:48.050
I have the right...

301
00:20:52.209 --> 00:20:53.569
Please don't hurt my son!

302
00:20:56.860 --> 00:20:57.860
Easy. easy.

303
00:20:58.000 --> 00:20:59.000
All of us.

304
00:20:59.484 --> 00:21:00.484
The young dog lost his head.

305
00:21:00.620 --> 00:21:01.620
Showing some mercy.

306
00:21:04.329 --> 00:21:05.336
Have some more of his wine.

307
00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:06.360
I'll take care of it.

308
00:21:07.519 --> 00:21:08.920
He is father's hunting dog.

309
00:21:10.509 --> 00:21:12.500
He lives only to
saw Odysseus return.

310
00:21:12.820 --> 00:21:13.240
That's fine.

311
00:21:13.435 --> 00:21:16.820
I will put it on the manure pile in front of the door so that
he could have welcomed his master a little earlier.

312
00:21:27.280 --> 00:21:28.900
That dog stays out there.

313
00:21:30.839 --> 00:21:33.479
Think twice next time
before sacrificing your life for an animal.

314
00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:46.320
You're Clint.

315
00:21:48.359 --> 00:21:50.880
Prepare supplies. take them to
Lodiam. don't tell anyone.

316
00:21:51.420 --> 00:21:52.660
Only use people you trust.

317
00:21:52.830 --> 00:21:54.400
You broke your mother's heart.

318
00:21:54.620 --> 00:21:56.320
If I stay. they will make me fight.

319
00:21:56.800 --> 00:21:57.800
No one will support me.

320
00:21:58.094 --> 00:22:00.000
I need to find out what happened to mine
father.

321
00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:03.540
Ithaca will follow me if
they find that Odysseus is dead.

322
00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:05.080
The suitors will never know.

323
00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:06.660
You will never come back alive.

324
00:22:06.661 --> 00:22:09.840
Tell Mentor to let me
he waits by the ships just before dawn.

325
00:22:10.439 --> 00:22:13.100
What should I say to your mother?

326
00:22:14.099 --> 00:22:15.520
To last as long as possible.

327
00:22:19.500 --> 00:22:20.180
The ship is ready.

328
00:22:20.515 --> 00:22:21.515
The tide is suitable.

329
00:22:22.409 --> 00:22:24.300
I told you already
ever that you have wise eyes?

330
00:22:24.715 --> 00:22:25.715
Athena's eyes?

331
00:22:26.180 --> 00:22:27.180
Once or twice.

332
00:22:27.495 --> 00:22:29.375
You haven't even asked me where yet 
we are going.

333
00:22:29.580 --> 00:22:30.580
Where are we going?

334
00:22:31.195 --> 00:22:32.195
Searching for my father.

335
00:22:32.760 --> 00:22:33.540
He is alive.

336
00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:35.280
I can feel it in the wind and in the waves.

337
00:22:35.340 --> 00:22:36.340
It's out there somewhere.

338
00:22:36.469 --> 00:22:37.469
He wanders.

339
00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:38.060
Wounded.

340
00:22:38.220 --> 00:22:38.480
Lost.

341
00:22:38.500 --> 00:22:39.500
I don't know.

342
00:22:40.220 --> 00:22:41.220
But he is alive.

343
00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:14.140
Dreams again?

344
00:23:15.640 --> 00:23:16.640
Men are drowning.

345
00:23:17.820 --> 00:23:18.820
Inside.

346
00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:21.800
In some...

347
00:23:22.099 --> 00:23:23.099
dark space.

348
00:23:25.899 --> 00:23:27.200
Firelight on stone.

349
00:23:27.500 --> 00:23:28.500
I don't know.

350
00:23:31.179 --> 00:23:32.259
Don't you want to remember?

351
00:23:32.819 --> 00:23:35.120
Why doesn't God speak
in a way that we understand?

352
00:23:38.259 --> 00:23:39.580
Who does not understand thunder?

353
00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:41.780
Fire.

354
00:23:42.569 --> 00:23:43.580
A child's smile.

355
00:23:43.820 --> 00:23:44.820
Good harvest.

356
00:23:45.489 --> 00:23:46.940
Are you hiding from us?

357
00:23:48.740 --> 00:23:49.740
Look.

358
00:23:50.939 --> 00:23:52.000
Who moves that cloud?

359
00:23:53.309 --> 00:23:54.360
Who calls those birds?

360
00:23:56.239 --> 00:23:57.239
Who moves the water?

361
00:23:59.759 --> 00:24:00.759
Who were you talking to?

362
00:24:03.919 --> 00:24:05.280
Athena came to me again.

363
00:24:06.149 --> 00:24:07.320
He tells me to remember.

364
00:24:09.240 --> 00:24:10.240
To leave.

365
00:24:11.099 --> 00:24:12.099
Why would you leave?

366
00:24:12.429 --> 00:24:13.680
We have everything we need.

367
00:24:14.799 --> 00:24:16.660
How long have I been here Calypso?

368
00:24:21.499 --> 00:24:22.900
I have a home somewhere.

369
00:24:25.109 --> 00:24:27.340
There's someone out there.

370
00:24:28.540 --> 00:24:29.540
How do you know that?

371
00:24:30.200 --> 00:24:31.200
I don't know.

372
00:24:33.580 --> 00:24:34.580
I feel it.

373
00:24:51.179 --> 00:24:52.659
What we have here could last forever.

374
00:24:53.089 --> 00:24:54.240
Eternity is for the gods.

375
00:24:54.850 --> 00:24:55.850
Are you a god?

376
00:24:58.669 --> 00:25:01.900
You want to remember. but what if you
memories rob you of happiness?

377
00:25:02.584 --> 00:25:03.740
Then it wasn't real.

378
00:25:12.010 --> 00:25:12.570
Nope.

379
00:25:13.030 --> 00:25:13.770
Not anymore.

380
00:25:13.830 --> 00:25:14.830
But I love it.

381
00:25:15.144 --> 00:25:16.430
Stop hating. Lotus.

382
00:25:17.519 --> 00:25:18.770
Tell me what you remember.

383
00:25:20.790 --> 00:25:21.790
After Troy.

384
00:25:23.810 --> 00:25:24.810
Troy.

385
00:25:31.289 --> 00:25:32.289
We won the war.

386
00:25:33.199 --> 00:25:34.199
And what then?

387
00:26:40.139 --> 00:26:41.830
Ten years on this fucking beach.

388
00:26:46.929 --> 00:26:48.010
Let's go home.

389
00:26:50.079 --> 00:26:51.210
Remember those we leave behind.

390
00:26:56.359 --> 00:26:57.519
Do we have enough stock?

391
00:26:58.654 --> 00:26:59.940
We took enough from Troy.

392
00:27:01.249 --> 00:27:02.680
A stop or two won't kill us.

393
00:27:10.860 --> 00:27:11.360
On the bow!

394
00:27:11.815 --> 00:27:12.815
At the stern!

395
00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:14.680
On the bow!

396
00:27:15.120 --> 00:27:16.120
Pull in the oars.

397
00:27:16.375 --> 00:27:17.375
Risk!

398
00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:18.400
Risk!

399
00:27:18.649 --> 00:27:19.740
Pull in the oars!

400
00:27:19.880 --> 00:27:20.980
Pull in the oars!

401
00:27:26.120 --> 00:27:27.320
We'll pull out the tarp.

402
00:27:27.540 --> 00:27:28.700
We follow the south wind.

403
00:27:28.820 --> 00:27:29.820
Yes. sir.

404
00:27:30.864 --> 00:27:33.120
Agamemnon is rowing west along the familiar path
supply route.

405
00:27:33.254 --> 00:27:34.600
He has more miles to feed.

406
00:27:35.659 --> 00:27:36.880
I'll find places for us to land.

407
00:27:37.340 --> 00:27:37.780
are you sure

408
00:27:37.860 --> 00:27:38.320
It's a risk.

409
00:27:38.694 --> 00:27:40.200
I have followed Agamemnon for quite some time.

410
00:27:41.189 --> 00:27:44.140
With a little luck and
we will see with the right wind

411
00:27:44.141 --> 00:27:47.001
a piece of the world and we will always be
home sooner than Agamemnon.

412
00:28:56.939 --> 00:28:58.440
Just leave the bear on the right.

413
00:29:15.469 --> 00:29:18.960
You lucky bastard. we have
only last stocks left.

414
00:29:19.354 --> 00:29:22.800
Assemble the airborne team. food and
water. and prepare for three weeks.

415
00:29:23.449 --> 00:29:24.529
What if they don't give it to us?

416
00:29:26.719 --> 00:29:28.120
How badly do you want to get home?

417
00:29:29.369 --> 00:29:30.840
Prepare your weapons!

418
00:29:31.195 --> 00:29:34.920
Begging. borrowing. looting.

419
00:29:39.259 --> 00:29:42.480
Ask them why they left theirs
the village instead of welcoming us.

420
00:29:48.480 --> 00:29:50.900
They say they thought
that we are sea people.

421
00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:51.260
Nope.

422
00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:53.000
We are Greeks.

423
00:29:53.720 --> 00:29:54.720
From Ithaca.

424
00:29:55.549 --> 00:29:56.989
You may have heard about
our victory at Troy.

425
00:29:57.859 --> 00:30:00.020
We are heading west with southerly winds.

426
00:30:07.209 --> 00:30:10.320
He says if we go there he won't
we like what we find there.

427
00:30:12.240 --> 00:30:18.140
After years of war. no one could
stand between my men and home.

428
00:30:19.709 --> 00:30:20.709
Not even me.

429
00:30:22.299 --> 00:30:23.320
Did something happen?

430
00:30:39.939 --> 00:30:41.400
We are chasing the runaway son.

431
00:30:46.080 --> 00:30:47.540
Let him like it.

432
00:30:50.624 --> 00:30:51.800
Lucky bastard.

433
00:31:04.469 --> 00:31:05.910
No. no. no. no.

434
00:31:06.599 --> 00:31:08.190
Sheep walk in flocks.

435
00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:11.110
Let's go after them.

436
00:32:31.949 --> 00:32:32.949
Someone lives here.

437
00:32:34.410 --> 00:32:35.410
Hey. they make cheese.

438
00:32:54.130 --> 00:32:55.130
Pretty good.

439
00:32:58.859 --> 00:32:59.859
There's a lot of it here.

440
00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:01.000
We should get out.

441
00:33:01.719 --> 00:33:03.159
We didn't bring anything to exchange.

442
00:33:03.850 --> 00:33:04.850
Law of Zeus.

443
00:33:05.239 --> 00:33:07.510
I don't know if the one who lives here
ever heard of Zeus' law.

444
00:33:07.511 --> 00:33:08.910
Or about Zeus. for that matter.

445
00:33:09.054 --> 00:33:10.570
Everyone has heard of Zeus' law.

446
00:33:11.339 --> 00:33:12.350
Build a fire.

447
00:33:12.670 --> 00:33:13.950
We welcome the owner when he returns.

448
00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:34.650
Away from the fire.

449
00:34:35.690 --> 00:34:35.909
No!

450
00:34:36.570 --> 00:34:36.570
No!

451
00:34:36.870 --> 00:34:37.870
No!

452
00:34:39.249 --> 00:34:40.330
Get distracted!

453
00:36:14.030 --> 00:36:15.240
I think he's sleeping.

454
00:37:00.560 --> 00:37:01.560
Wait.

455
00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:14.960
We won't move that boulder.

456
00:37:15.230 --> 00:37:16.230
We would be trapped.

457
00:37:25.350 --> 00:37:25.830
Sure.

458
00:37:26.150 --> 00:37:27.150
In the morning.

459
00:37:27.375 --> 00:37:28.730
When he drives out his flock.

460
00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:30.270
We burst into the entrance.

461
00:37:31.130 --> 00:37:32.130
Take a rest.

462
00:38:17.760 --> 00:38:22.240
We can stuff something in
cave opening. leave a gap?

463
00:38:23.420 --> 00:38:24.420
Maybe.

464
00:38:25.420 --> 00:38:26.420
But what?

465
00:38:26.960 --> 00:38:27.960
It's locked.

466
00:38:31.700 --> 00:38:32.700
He will notice.

467
00:38:34.680 --> 00:38:36.880
But take the thin end. put it in the fire.

468
00:38:37.765 --> 00:38:39.340
How many ropes do we have?

469
00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:41.280
How big is the flock?

470
00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:42.400
A few dozen. maybe.

471
00:38:45.260 --> 00:38:46.260
There are too many of us.

472
00:38:47.070 --> 00:38:49.460
When he comes back. two of us have to get out.

473
00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:50.680
Or at least fall.

474
00:38:56.190 --> 00:38:59.260
Run low through the flock to
entrance. then split up.

475
00:38:59.520 --> 00:39:00.940
So that we can catch just one of them.

476
00:39:01.280 --> 00:39:01.540
Good.

477
00:39:02.055 --> 00:39:03.340
Four of us should go.

478
00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:04.480
Two and two.

479
00:39:04.860 --> 00:39:06.120
Why risk more men?

480
00:39:06.365 --> 00:39:07.685
Last night there were not two of us.

481
00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:09.470
He'll want two more before he falls asleep.

482
00:39:34.390 --> 00:39:35.390
Run. run. run!

483
00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:47.600
I...

484
00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:48.920
I'm worth nothing!

485
00:41:14.100 --> 00:41:15.100
What about his body?

486
00:41:15.730 --> 00:41:16.730
What should it be?

487
00:41:16.845 --> 00:41:18.050
Should we just let him rot here?

488
00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:20.690
Like food for that thing?

489
00:41:22.880 --> 00:41:25.010
We are to honor our dead. Odysseus.

490
00:41:25.730 --> 00:41:27.050
He died to help us escape.

491
00:41:27.130 --> 00:41:28.290
We will honor him by running away.

492
00:41:42.510 --> 00:41:43.830
He can talk.

493
00:41:45.450 --> 00:41:46.650
Why didn't he speak before?

494
00:41:48.580 --> 00:41:49.690
Are you talking to ants?

495
00:41:51.650 --> 00:41:52.910
Should we negotiate with it?

496
00:41:55.710 --> 00:41:57.690
I think we are over it.

497
00:43:07.400 --> 00:43:09.120
what are you doing

498
00:43:10.044 --> 00:43:11.044
No!

499
00:43:52.350 --> 00:43:53.350
Give me the gun!

500
00:43:58.930 --> 00:44:01.730
What is it?

501
00:44:07.775 --> 00:44:13.180
who is that

502
00:44:26.620 --> 00:44:27.100
Run!

503
00:44:27.200 --> 00:44:27.460
Run!

504
00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:27.860
Run!

505
00:44:28.120 --> 00:44:28.600
Run!

506
00:44:28.601 --> 00:44:28.760
Run!

507
00:44:29.520 --> 00:44:30.520
Run!

508
00:44:31.240 --> 00:44:32.240
Run!

509
00:44:52.740 --> 00:44:54.210
Why did you have to shoot that arrow?

510
00:44:54.610 --> 00:44:56.997
We lost good ones
soldiers because of that beast. yes.

511
00:44:56.998 --> 00:45:00.751
and that beast was the son of Poseidon What?

512
00:45:01.320 --> 00:45:05.150
When he gouged out his eye. we heard how
screaming his name That thing was a monster.

513
00:45:05.600 --> 00:45:06.630
I heard that too.

514
00:45:07.750 --> 00:45:09.170
So now the sea is against us?

515
00:45:09.590 --> 00:45:10.590
And the wind.

516
00:45:11.620 --> 00:45:14.030
How are we supposed to get home when it is
Poseidon against us?

517
00:45:14.190 --> 00:45:16.310
We cannot live on signs and sacrifices alone.

518
00:45:18.950 --> 00:45:20.741
You know how many times I have you
heard crying

519
00:45:20.742 --> 00:45:22.790
pray to Athena since we left Troy?

520
00:45:23.430 --> 00:45:24.830
Couldn't she show some mercy?

521
00:45:26.290 --> 00:45:27.290
Take this.

522
00:45:29.550 --> 00:45:30.550
Wear it.

523
00:45:31.300 --> 00:45:32.830
To remember those we could not bury.

524
00:45:34.810 --> 00:45:36.690
The gods help those who help themselves.

525
00:45:40.700 --> 00:45:45.710
From that moment every stormy sea or
the headwind was telling the crew that we were cursed.

526
00:45:48.500 --> 00:45:49.500
But where is my crew?

527
00:45:51.710 --> 00:45:53.290
When will you let me see my men?

528
00:45:54.620 --> 00:45:56.740
If I could talk to them. they would help
me to remember.

529
00:45:57.330 --> 00:45:58.330
Did I have a wife?

530
00:45:58.490 --> 00:45:58.870
Children?

531
00:45:59.070 --> 00:46:00.070
Maybe a son?

532
00:46:00.300 --> 00:46:01.340
How long have I been here?

533
00:46:03.250 --> 00:46:04.250
A long time.

534
00:46:05.290 --> 00:46:09.830
If I had a son. how old would he be now?

535
00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:13.830
I don't know how to speak to a king.

536
00:46:14.250 --> 00:46:15.250
You'll be fine.

537
00:46:15.630 --> 00:46:16.630
Keep your mouth shut.

538
00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:22.250
But if anyone asks. we are traitors from
Crete and we will figure out how

539
00:46:22.350 --> 00:46:23.350
address the king.

540
00:46:33.250 --> 00:46:34.250
Welcome.

541
00:46:34.510 --> 00:46:35.510
Thank you.

542
00:46:35.860 --> 00:46:36.900
Looks like you're having a good time.

543
00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:38.010
Here.

544
00:46:42.880 --> 00:46:44.040
Where are you taking us?

545
00:46:44.440 --> 00:46:47.020
The king insists on being with foreigners
